docs.abstract: Ms. Tlaib, who won a Democratic primary in Michigan, may become the first Muslim woman in Congress. She said her upbringing shaped her political vision.
docs.snippet: Ms. Tlaib, who won a Democratic primary in Michigan, may become the first Muslim woman in Congress. She said her upbringing shaped her political vision.
docs.lead_paragraph: DETROIT — The family was standing outside the black iron fence of Detroit’s Immigration and Customs Enforcement center, named after Rosa Parks, to protest news of their father’s sudden deportation, when Rashida Tlaib appeared and took up a bullhorn.

headline.main: For Rashida Tlaib, Palestinian Heritage Infuses a Detroit Sense of Community
headline.print_headline: Candidate’s Palestinian Heritage Infuses Sense of Community in Detroit

docs.abstract: The 77-year-old democratic socialist from Vermont made clear that he could still own the Democratic debate. And the debate stage.

docs.lead_paragraph: Bernie Sanders was at it again — center stage, his baritone building to something — right hand raised and restless, as if he were scribbling his words on an invisible chalkboard.

headline.main: Bernie Sanders ‘Wrote the Damn Bill.’ Everyone Else Is Just Fighting About It.
headline.print_headline: Sanders Takes Center Stage, Along With the Bill He Wrote

docs.lead_paragraph: CLEAR LAKE, Iowa — The Democratic presidential candidates paused here for a moment of silence for the victims of the mass shootings in El Paso and Dayton, Ohio, underscoring how the turbulent events of the past week have refocused the primary contest.

headline.main: At Iowa’s Wing Ding Dinner, Democrats Assail G.O.P. on Gun Control

docs.abstract: Fourteen candidates are assured a place onstage. The rest are battling it out for six remaining slots. In September, things get tougher.
docs.snippet: Fourteen candidates are assured a place onstage. The rest are battling it out for six remaining slots. In September, things get tougher.
docs.lead_paragraph: With just four weeks to go until the second set of Democratic presidential primary debates, a handful of lower-tier candidates are in danger of missing them. A single percentage point of support in one poll could be the difference between getting invited to Detroit and being left off the debate stage.

headline.main: Here Are the Democrats at Risk of Not Making the July Debates
headline.print_headline: Tight Race for Last Slots In Next Debates, and Bar Is Only Getting Higher

docs.lead_paragraph: Senator Cory Booker, tieless and in a blazer on the southwestern border in early July, approached a Customs and Border Protection officer, blue passport in hand. They greeted each other and the officer asked: “Is there somebody with you?” Yes, Mr. Booker said, he had a group with him.

headline.main: Cory Booker’s Brand of Advocacy: Show Up. Cameras Often Follow.

docs.abstract: The fatal shooting last week of a black man by a South Bend police officer has tested Mr. Buttigieg’s leadership at a critical time for his campaign.
docs.snippet: The fatal shooting last week of a black man by a South Bend police officer has tested Mr. Buttigieg’s leadership at a critical time for his campaign.
docs.lead_paragraph: SOUTH BEND, Ind. — It has been one of the biggest challenges for Pete Buttigieg since he began his improbable presidential campaign in January: Could the Harvard-educated mayor of South Bend, who often comes across like the brainy technocrat he once was as a McKinsey & Company consultant, build a following among black voters, one of the Democratic Party’s most vital constituencies?

headline.main: At Town Hall, Pete Buttigieg Confronts Tensions Around South Bend Police Shooting
headline.print_headline: Shooting Fuels Racial Tensions And Puts Buttigieg in Hot Seat

byline.original: By Mitch Smith and Alexander Burns
